segments.text: Yes, could you tell us your full name?
My name is Bonnie Sue Shelton Stadelman.
And could you tell us when and where you were born?
I was born in Boulder, Colorado, June the 18th, 1934.
as far back as you can remember with grade school, if you wish, and bring it on up to the time that you acquired your Ph.D. Well, I attended elementary schools in Toledo, Ohio and Waterville, Ohio.
I went to high school in Waterville, Ohio my first two years, then transferred to Maumee Valley Country Day School where I had a scholarship.
From there, I went to Earlham College, which is a Quaker college in Richmond, Indiana, for two years.
I transferred to Ohio State where I got a BS in 1956.
Then I taught school for two years in Durham, Connecticut.
Even though I had a bachelor's degree in social science, I taught biology and math.
Then I got my master's degree at Western Reserve University in Cleveland, Ohio in 1960.
I expected that with a master's degree I'd be able to teach history, but the coaches still had that field all sewed up.
So I ended up in Chalmette, Louisiana teaching biology and general science.
Then I started to Tulane in
fall of 1964, and I got my PhD in American Colonial History in August 1969.
Then what did you do after you received your PhD?
Well, I was already employed here on the staff.
I see.
I see.
When and why did you come to A&M to teach?
I was married at the time, and my husband was on the philosophy faculty.
I see.
And I sort of haunted Dr. Nance's office.
And the Latin American historian, I believe his name was Dr. Ewan, or McEwan, had a heart attack and collapsed in his office.
And so they needed somebody in the middle of the year.
So I fit right in in January of 1968.
I see.
And what were your primary teaching responsibilities at this time?
I've been a perpetual freshman teaching History 105 and 106 exclusively except for one semester when David Morgan was on leave and I taught Colonial American History.
And what was your normal teaching load during the whole year by semester?
When I started it was 12 hours and then when Dean Maxwell
came as the head of liberal arts.
He shifted it to a nine hour load.
I see.
And what did you teach in the summer time?
Did you teach one semester or two semesters in the summer?
The first couple of summers I taught two courses, one term or the other in summer school.
Then there were a couple of summers I didn't teach at all, by choice.
And then
Let's see, it must have been the summer of 1972 they gave me one course one summer term and one course the second summer term.
Because I was at the bottom of the totem pole and was lucky to get any summer teaching at all.
Then the last two summers I've taught two courses the first summer term.
Now, at any time while you were here, was your work criticized in any way?
No.
No, I never was praised, but that was par for the course.
Nobody else got praised either.
But there were strong hints, of course, that faculty were expected to publish articles.
But I published an article in the William & Mary Quarterly, which I felt was pretty good feather.
When did you first learn that you would not be granted tenure?
What was your first inclination that you were going to have problems with the tenure?
It never crossed my mind that there would be any problem until April of 1972.
I was on the verge of getting a divorce, and I wanted to tell Dr. Nance so that he wouldn't find it out by the grapevine or read it in the newspaper.
And I was very overwrought emotionally, and I could hardly talk to him.
And I told him about my personal affairs, and he chose that moment to unload the fact that not he, but some members of the department felt that people who only taught
History 105 and 106 should not be given tenure.
And I was in such a state that the import of what he was saying only began to penetrate.
Well, let's get something clear right now.
Do you have a choice in what you teach?
No.
Never?
No, not at all.
So that's kind of unusual to tell you about that.
Well, it made it sound as if it was a diabolical plot on my part.
to refuse to teach advanced courses when actually everybody wants to teach advanced courses.
But you were never, never given the opportunity to, except for the one time when Dave Morgan was on leave.
But there was a prevailing atmosphere that everything would come to those who waited patiently, that their turn would come, that you served your apprenticeship.
Yes, I understand that.
I see.
Well, then after this, do you remember when this conference was?
April, 72.
Then after that, then what?
Could you give us sort of a chronological breakdown of what was happening?
Well, it was just a matter of waiting.
But then in the fall, I got a letter saying that I had been made a member of the graduate faculty.
So I considered that a very positive sign.
I didn't think they would put someone on the graduate faculty that they were about to fire.
And then, simultaneously with the meeting of the

tenure and promotion committee which consisted of all the full professors in the department there was a curriculum committee that met and there were two people who were members of both committees one was dr nance and one was dr hall the curriculum committee at this time assigned me a graduate course cultural history from the beginning to 1865 history 625
And I was to work out a course outline, a bibliography.
And I thought that this was a very positive sign because it would meet this requirement that I teach something besides History 105 and 106.
I thought, as a matter of fact, they had purposely gone out of their way to cover that.
So you felt probably very relieved at that time.
Well, I interpreted it positively, but there was still considerable anxiety.
I see.
Because I knew that the committee had met, the Promotion and Tenure Committee met.
It must have been early in December of 1972.
Can you tell us who was on this committee?
All the full professors, which, you want them by name?
You might go ahead.
All right.
It would have been Dr. Nance, Claude Hall,
Herb Lang, Haskell Monroe, Betty Underberger, Tom Miller, Alan Ashcraft, and Lloyd Taylor.
Six of those voted.
Dr. Nance and Haskell Monroe excused themselves.
But the decision had been made, and I knew it had been made, but they were not telling.
Nobody was telling.

So I approached Dean Maxwell just on the verge of a Christmas vacation because I was going to attend the American Historical Association convention in New Orleans and I wanted to know so that I knew how seriously I had to pursue John Prospects.
And the dean claimed that he didn't know what the decision was yet.
I see.
And he wouldn't tell me.
So I went to the convention not knowing.
Dr. Unterberger rode with me to New Orleans, and she would not reveal the decision.
I placed you handicapped at a place where, well, the slave market may be dead, but at least there are some jobs available.
Well, at least I could have made some effort.
Yes, that's what's interesting.
Well, go on.
What happened after that?
Well, I returned...
not having very seriously pursued the job thing, because I really felt fairly confident.
I thought I had done a good job at Texas A&M.
But I needed to know, definitely.
So the second day of the semester, the second semester, in January of 1973, I went to Dean Maxwell's office.
I had an appointment.
And I said, I want to know.
told me that the decision was negative.
And for about the next three months, I walked around in a state of shock.
I see.
I did not miss a class.
My students didn't know what had happened to me.
And so I went right on functioning.
About the first

action that I had the presence of mind to take was in February, I made an appointment with Dr. Williams and told him that I didn't expect him to upset the whole system by going back and reversing the decision.

but that I would like for him to find me some other position somewhere on the campus because this was my home and I love Texas A&M and I felt that there was still a service that I could make to the university.
So he asked me to write a letter making this request and several weeks later he replied saying that he could not find anything in the whole system that would utilize my talents.
Then at the end of February or early in March, I started a barrage of letters to all sorts of people.
I guess I had to give credit to my father for being the spirit who stood behind me and said, stand and fight.
He said, your best chance is here at Texas A&M.
So I wrote to...

H-E-W, I wrote to the EEOC, I wrote to the AHA, I wrote to the AAUP, I wrote to Francis Farenthold, I wrote to many people, trying to find out what support I could get, hoping that I could line up a rather formidable array of support, and then approach the administration and say, look, let's do something, or I'm going to train.

artillery yes but the eeoc sort of blew the whole case open i always understood that when the government hew or any of these agencies corresponded with you that they never let your name be known to your employers for feeling some sort of retaliation so it came as quite a
surprised to me when some of my friends in the history department acted very icy, virtual icicles in the air.
And the whole thing back of it was that the Equal Employment Opportunities Commission had sent a form to President Williams giving my name and saying that a complaint had been filed in my name.
on a charge of sex discrimination.
And he had circulated this to the dean and to the history department.
And they considered this not really playing very fair, going, squealing at the government.
Actually, I hadn't filed the complaint.
All I had done was to write a letter stating, this is what happened to me.
Can you help me?
But on the basis of my letter of inquiry, they had
informed the whole administration, so there was really nothing to do but to go ahead and notarize that formal complaint.
I think this was probably a good thing.
Well, yeah, it forced my hand earlier than I had expected, but it worked out well.
Certainly.
And not very long after that, I employed an attorney.
How did you go about selecting an attorney?
Well, again, I have to give my father credit.
They spend their winters in southern Texas.
On their return to Ohio, my dad had been reading the local news sheet.
This was about the time that Sarah Weddington had taken the case to the Supreme Court, the Texas abortion law case, and had gotten it declared unconstitutional.
So her name was in the news.
Dad's feeling was that we don't want just any lawyer.
We're going to get a good lawyer.
Somebody who might even have a political stake in it.
Who might get some mileage out of the case if it ever went to court.
So I wrote to both Frances Ferrentholdt and Sarah, I called Sarah Weddington on the phone and she took the case.
What was her reaction, her first reaction to the case when you called her?
Did she thank you?
had a reasonable case?
Well, nothing could be determined until I talked to her about it.
So I made a trip over to Austin and talked to her for at least an hour.
I see.
I was very impressed with her.
I was very pleased with her as an attorney.
She was not one of these boat rockers that figures walk.
Let's go out for publicity.
Let's make as many waves as possible.
All of her counsel was
well, let's play it quietly and not get people's backs up, not put them on the defensive until there is no other recourse.
There's plenty of time for wave making if they're totally obstinate.
And she must have felt that I had a case because she took it.
Well, then what was your next step?
after you acquired or retained a lawyer.
What was her advice to you at this point?
Just to wait until the Equal Employment Opportunities Commission made their investigation and made a report.
Plus, I needed to
follow all avenues of appeal on campus because there was no possibility of going to court until all other possibilities had been exhausted.
But there was plenty of time for that in the fall.
The Equal Employment Opportunities Commission said that they were overloaded with cases and they didn't know when they would get to me, but they put mine on a fast track.
And I expected them here
in June, but it was July when Brenda Becker came from San Antonio.
I talked to her and she talked to several people on campus.

It was sort of interesting that when she informed the administration that she was coming, they set up an appointment with Ray Smith, who is the head of personnel, which sounds like a very logical place to send her, except
Ray Smith is in charge of janitors and maids.
He's in charge of staff, not faculty.
Right.
Dr. Calhoun is the faculty.
So I informed her of what they had done, and I think that she felt somewhat enlightened by that revelation.
That's interesting.
Well, do you know what transpired between Smith and Becker?
Well, he apparently was the one that she worked with to get the records.
And she told the university what records she wanted.
Personnel files.
And these had to be subpoenaed.
And the university talked her out of as many files as she requested.
I think it finally got down to all people who were up for tenure in 1972, plus probably all women on campus, on the faculty.
And then the university opened these files.
All people whose files were subpoenaed had an opportunity to go and look at their files.
So in August, I looked at my file and found that it was sketchy.
there were things missing, that the evidence on which they made the decision in my case was only partially there.
Did you inform Becker?
Yes, and also Dr. Calhoun, and my record was, the gaps were filled in.
Almost put back together again.
Well, it was sort of interesting, every year we have to make out these
Form 3s, which tells what you've been doing all year.
But it was also part of the instructions.
We didn't need to put in things that we had done every year.
I see.
And these are the things that they used to make the tenure, promotion, salary increases.
But they hadn't all those on file.
They had only looked at the most recent one, which left my whole honest story.
I see.
So, Ms. Becker buried herself in those files and she told me that she should have a preliminary report ready by the first of August.
No, no, the first of September.
But the first of October came and of course my phone bell mounted because
very patiently, kept checking with her.
And the first of November came.
She was sick for quite a while in November, and the first of December came.
But just before Christmas vacation, I called her.
And off the record, not for telling anybody, she said that she was
presenting a letter of determination in my favor.
Her superior might change it.
The chances weren't very strong that he would, but he might.
But for my own peace of mind at least, I could go off to San Francisco to the American Historical Convention knowing that this letter was in the works.
Well, they were having a typing crisis.
Apparently they only had one typist in the office there in San Antonio to do all their work.
And so even though the letter was in the mail, it would be the end of January before it would get typed.
I volunteered to go over and type it myself.
Certainly.
So Sarah Weddington got on the phone for me.
And she had some connections.
So it got typed maybe a couple of weeks earlier than that.
I received my letter of determination on a Saturday, and of course the administrative offices weren't open, so I knew before Dr. Williams knew, and I knew what was coming in his mail Monday morning.
And at that point, things began to fall into place.
Well, what happened after the administration received the letter of determination?
Well, I guess I should back up a little bit.
I forgot one kind of interesting episode.
I went to see Dr. Calhoun at the end of Christmas Vacation.
Sarah Weddington had advised me to ask him about summer teaching.
My contract ended May 4th.
But she suggested that I talk to him about teaching in the summer.
Well, he brushed that off.
He said, well, I don't know.
He said, go back and ask Dr. Gooch to approach me on this.
But he said, my understanding is that your employment ends, and so that's probably the end of that.
And then I asked him, what if the government should find in my favor?
knowing that my letter was probably on the way.
And his reaction was, how could they?
I don't see any way that they could uphold your charge of sex discrimination.
So I smiled knowingly and didn't reveal that I knew that such a letter was coming.
He spent most of the interview discussing what he would do if he were me.
He was trying to advise me.
To leave?
Well, no.
I really appreciated it very much, and I trusted his sincerity.
He gave me a list of several things that he would do for me.
This was an unprecedented case.
He didn't like overturning administrative decisions.
It was sort of almost a matter of faith that it was sin to change a decision
However, I could ask.
And this would be putting him on a terrible spot.
And he wished that I wouldn't put him on a spot.
But since I had exhausted all other appeals, he was opening a new court of appeals if he would reconsider my case.
And on the basis of the fact that I had a new chairman and it was a whole new ballgame,
David Morgan, who had been the colonial historian, was gone, and now they could no longer say that I was a duplication.
On the basis of the fact that no rules on tenure had been published, no guidelines, no standards, what do we expect in people who are being granted tenure?
In other words, you don't have one within the department.
No.
A tenure statement.
Nor in the university.
That's funny, because it's the first thing the library did.
When we got faculty status over there, this you will do.
This is what is required of you.
No, there was nothing.
Not in the university, not in the College of Liberal Arts, not in the department.
And Calhoun himself published one, but it was December of 73 when he did it.
Oh, I see.
It was December of 73, yeah.
So it was a whole year after he'd been fired that he came up with a guideline.
So adding all those things, he said, go back and write me a letter stating all these reasons why I should open up your case again.
Well, before I got the letter written, oh, he didn't want me to write the letter until he informed me that he was ready to receive the letter.
And before that happened, they got the letter of determination from the EEOC.
And nothing happened immediately.
But in February, this is 74, there was a meeting of the board, one of the quarterly meetings of the board of directors.
And Dr. Monroe had made a statement in the paper that the board of directors would no doubt be discussing my case, so I wanted to be there and hear what they had to say about me.
Well, I didn't want to sit in on everything, so I wanted to find an agenda and see just where on the agenda my case fell.
So I called Dr. Williams' office to find out what the agenda was.
And they referred me to Mr. Cherry's office.
So I called over there.
Oh, I was referred to Dr. Calhoun's office.
Well, pretty soon the word spread around that Dr. Statham was looking for an agenda.
And Mr. Cherry called me and said,
Everybody has a right to see this agenda.
You come right in immediately.
So I went to Dr. Cherry's office, looked through the agenda.
I was not on the agenda.
And one of the things, this is the annual meeting where they decide who was to be given tenure, and they had a list of all the people who were to be given tenure.
Oh, I think I've left something out.
Yeah, I think you're on the punchline.
I had been verbally told that I would,
had tenure, and I had a letter from Dr. Calhoun, but I was not on the list for tenure, and I wondered why.
And this troubled me somewhat.
Well, let's see, there is something backwards here.
Now, I didn't know yet.
Well, at any rate, Dr. Calhoun called me in, and immediately.
The instructions were, at your earliest convenience, come in.
He was in a meeting of the deans, and he came bringing Dean Maxwell, and he said, what Dean Maxwell has to tell you I think will make you very happy.
If there are any questions, you can see me after this meeting.
but I don't believe it'll be necessary for you to attend that board of directors meeting.
So then Dean Maxwell sat down with me and told me that I had tenure and that all was well.
And then you received a letter shortly after that?
Yeah, I got a letter from Dr. Calhoun.
Confirming this.
But I still, now that the events are, there's still a cart and a horse mixed up here.
Because I was still very concerned about why I was not on the official list.
No action had been taken.
Well, about this time, there was an initiation of a freshman honors society, and I was made a member.
And Mrs. Smith, the only woman on the board of directors, was giving the address, and arrangements were made that I could be there so I could meet her.
And I asked her if they had discussed me at the meeting.
And she said, no, the issue never came up.
I said, well, in any of the behind-the-scenes meetings was my case discussed?
No, nothing was discussed.
So I was very concerned about this because Dr. Nance and maybe some others were saying, the case isn't settled.
She doesn't have tenure.
The board of directors didn't do it.
And my friends were beseeching me, why wasn't your name in the paper?
Why weren't you on the list?
And so I still felt very uneasy about it.
And so Dr. Calhoun called me in again and said, isn't this enough?
You've gotten a letter.
It's in writing.
You have tenure.
And about a couple of days after that, after Dr. Calhoun and I had a very firm understanding and a very pleasant conversation, I got a phone call from Dr. Williams.
Why had I approached Mrs. Smith?
Why did I bring this up?
He hadn't really wanted the Board of Directors to know about this.
It's true, the Board of Directors are the only ones that could grant tenure, but Dr. Calhoun, I had it in writing it would hold up in any court, wasn't I?
Satisfying.
Well, what had happened was Mrs. Smith, after she gave her little talk, spent the night at Dr. Williams' house and had asked him about me.
And so he was distressed that I had gone to the board of directors, or one of the board of directors, about the case, because he hadn't wanted to trouble them with the whole thing.
That simply by being here and teaching next fall, I would have de facto tenure
And next spring, next February, when they have their list, my name will be on that list.
By that time, the board of directors will have forgotten about the case.

Whereas if he had come into this last meeting and said, oh, I want you to add one more name, and had said, here's the name, they would have said, Bonnie Stadelman, isn't she the one that's suing the university?
And then there would have been a big hoover-off.
I doubt it.
Well, that's what he is.
thinking wise.
They probably would never have noticed had they changed the list, saying, we have a list change here.
We've left a name off.
Well, he felt that it would create all sorts of disturbance.
And so... At least they could have informed you of why they were going to do this.
Yeah.
Well, I wasn't.
And so I walked into a sticky situation.
Listen to me.
It just seems to me it could have been done
For one thing, I doubt that the board would ever have looked at the entire list of names.
It's usually done by... Well, you see, the agenda is a very official looking thing.
It's a great big document.
And to come in and say, oh, add this one name.
And Dr. Williams, I believe, had called each of the members of the board personally about my case after the letter of determination came in.
And his feeling...
from sort of an unofficial poll of the board of directors was, let's fight it.
We don't want the government telling us what to do.
And so he figured that it would create quite a stir.
Who do you think decided to capitulate?
I think this was Dr. Calhoun's decision.
I have to give him credit with being, having enough vision to be able to change a decision.
He had a meeting with Dr. Gooch about the time the letter of determination came in.
And then he called a meeting of all the full professors in the history department.
And I can only report this as hearsay.
But it came from two different sources that he said, I am an engineer.
I have to rely on you people for determining people's qualifications in history.
I can't make these decisions.
And you people have told me that she's not of the caliber that we want here at Texas A&M.
But the government looks at her record and says that she is qualified.
And Dr. Gooch comes in as head of the department.
He's more or less an outsider.
And he tells me that she is qualified.
Now, what was your thinking on this?
And in turn, each professor had to justify his vote.
And at this point, there was considerable squirming, considerable alarm that they might have to testify in court.
And many of them did not wish to be subjected to court interrogation.
would have been much worse than simply a friendly questioning by Calhoun, because then there's an opportunity to cross-examine.
Interesting, yes, very interesting.
And Dr. Gooch let it be known that the administration's case would look very bad in court.
At this time, especially, yes.
And he and Dr. Nance had a very heated discussion in Calhoun's office over...
whether to go to court, and Dr. Nance wanted to go to court with it.
Again, hearsay.
That's very interesting.
And I was quite willing and ready to take it to court, if nothing else.
Oh, yes, naturally, you had nothing to lose.
And with the government behind me, with those rather interesting statistics about how
few women there were at Texas A&M on the faculty.
And so this is where it stands now, you don't have to wait until the board meets again?
Well, that's a mere formality.
I see, I see.
Could you possibly tell us any other names of people who gave you support during this period off the university, outside?
Well, the American Historical Association has a committee on women, which was in regular correspondence with me.
And there wasn't much they could do, but they were willing to do whatever could be done.
And this is one of the things that caused Dr. Williams some anguish, because he didn't realize that I had been writing to them.
And so it came as kind of a surprise when I had the clear blue sky.
He got a letter offering their good services and mediating and so forth.
I saw the letter.
I read it very hastily.
Dr. Gooch has a copy of that letter.
And it seemed like a very moderate letter.
But Dr. Williams' reaction was, this is meddling.
It was unprofessional.
And he'd been a member of the AHA.
since he got his PhD and he was quite distressed that I had appealed to them and they had jumped into this whole thing.
I had a lot of support from other faculty members, people who kept checking with me continually, how is it coming, what's happening.
But the most gratifying of all was the support from the students.
My students were just wonderful.
I received many letters and even more verbal reassurances that I was a worthy teacher.
Well, when you look at it, really, what other point is there for you being here?
Well, this is my thinking.
This is a university, and without the students, the whole place is nothing.
But apparently the higher you get in the administration, the less contact they have with students, the more they forget that.
Well, as you look back now over the whole thing, do you have any words of wisdom?
Oh, I feel much wiser now that it's happened.
happened to me.
I have never failed at anything.
And to come up against a failure at this point in life was really soul-wrenching.
But now that it's over, I have learned a lot.
I am not as naive as I once was.
I am much more aware of political happenings
in a faculty.
I have tested the limits of my strength somewhat and found that I was a lot stronger than I thought I was.
I've learned a lot about myself in the process.
And whereas I probably don't deserve as much credit as I get, because without the government, it wouldn't have amounted to too much.
But nevertheless,
I understand that a lot of women give up somewhere along the line.
But I didn't back down.
I wonder, do you hold any of this against the university per se?
Do you still like A&M?
Oh, I still like A&M, yes.
And no, bitterness only is an acid that only corrodes the person who's holding it.
The department under Dr. Gooch is a whole different universe.
It's much warmer, friendlier.
The members of the department who voted against me are very civil, friendly even.
The issue is never discussed, and it's as if it never happened.
And I guess most of all, rather than finding that I was destroyed by failure, I learned what support I had, what friends I had, and most important, how the students felt about it.
And I think I like to, I don't know about you, but I like to feel that the students are aiming at the administration and the faculty particularly.
Anything else you'd like to comment on?
I'll probably think of something later.
